# Room 34 Hydra

## Task 1 Hydra Introduction
Objective: Understand Hydra fundamentals.
- Hydra is a brute force online password cracking tool.
- Automates login attempts across multiple protocols (SSH, FTP, HTTP forms, etc.).
- Importance: highlights why strong, complex passwords are necessary.
- Weak/default credentials (e.g., admin:password) are easily compromised.

---

## Task 2 Using Hydra

Objective: Learn how to set up and run Hydra.
- Hydra is preinstalled on AttackBox (TryHackMe environment).
- Requires attacker machine + target machine setup.
- Can also be installed on Linux distros (Ubuntu: apt install hydra, Fedora: dnf install hydra).
- Official repository provides protocol-specific options.
- Objective: Explore Hydra syntax for SSH brute force.
Command:
Code
- hydra -l <username> -P <password_list> MACHINE_IP -t 4 ssh
Options:
- -l → username.
- -P → password list.
- -t → threads (parallel attempts).
Example:
Code
- hydra -l root -P passwords.txt MACHINE_IP -t 4 ssh
Hydra will:
- Use root as username.
- Try all passwords in passwords.txt.
- Run 4 threads simultaneously.
- Task 4 Hydra Commands (Web Form Example)
Objective: Brute force web login forms with Hydra.
Command:
Code
- hydra -l <username> -P <wordlist> MACHINE_IP http-post-form "<path>:<login_credentials>:<invalid_response>" -V
Options:
- -l → username.
- -P → password list.
- http-post-form → specifies POST method.
<path> → login page (e.g., login.php).
- <login_credentials> → username=^USER^&password=^PASS^.
- <invalid_response> → string returned when login fails (e.g., F=incorrect).
- -V → verbose output.
Example:
- Code
- hydra -l admin -P wordlist.txt MACHINE_IP http-post-form "/:username=^USER^&password=^PASS^:F=incorrect" -V
Notes:
Replace ^USER^ and ^PASS^ dynamically.
Can specify non-default ports with -s <port>.

