## Tools Used

- Hydra (preinstalled on AttackBox).
- Password lists (e.g., rockyou.txt).
- Browser developer tools (to inspect form requests).

## Findings

- Hydra demonstrates the risk of weak/default credentials.
- Supports brute force across many protocols (SSH, FTP, HTTP, SNMP, etc.).
- Parallel threads accelerate brute force attempts.
- Web forms require identifying request type (GET/POST) and failure response strings.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Always change default credentials.
- Use strong passwords (length > 8, special characters, non-dictionary).
- Implement account lockout policies after failed attempts.
- Monitor logs for brute force activity.
- Use multi-factor authentication (MFA).

## Conclusion

- Hydra is a powerful brute force tool for testing authentication security.
- Demonstrates why password hygiene and defensive measures are critical.
- Understanding Hydra commands helps defenders anticipate and mitigate brute force attacks.
